    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": "# Synthetic CSI-Like Signal Exploration for Fall Detection\n\nThis notebook demonstrates a beginner-friendly workflow for WiFi CSI-inspired fall detection using synthetic CSI-like time-series signals.\n\n**Disclaimer:** This repository currently uses synthetic CSI-like time-series data for demonstration purposes. It does not use real patient data, real clinical data, or validated WiFi CSI measurements. Results are intended only to demonstrate the research workflow and should not be interpreted as clinical or real-world fall detection performance.\n\n## How to Read This Notebook\n\nThis notebook is intended to show the structure of an early research workflow:\n\n1. Generate synthetic CSI-like signals.\n2. Visualize normal and fall-like examples.\n3. Apply simple preprocessing.\n4. Extract basic time-series features.\n5. Train a baseline scikit-learn classifier.\n6. Evaluate results on synthetic data.\n7. Discuss limitations and next steps.\n\nThe results should be interpreted only as a demonstration of the workflow, not as evidence of real-world fall detection performance.\n"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": "## 1. Introduction and Disclaimer\n\nWiFi Channel State Information (CSI) can describe how wireless signals propagate through an environment. In WiFi sensing research, human motion can affect CSI amplitude and phase, which may support contactless sensing tasks such as activity recognition, vital-sign monitoring, or fall detection.\n\nThis notebook does **not** use real WiFi CSI data. Instead, it creates simple synthetic CSI-like signals to demonstrate a basic workflow: signal generation, visualization, preprocessing, feature extraction, baseline classification, and evaluation.\n\n**Exact repository disclaimer:** This repository currently uses synthetic CSI-like time-series data for demonstration purposes. It does not use real patient data, real clinical data, or validated WiFi CSI measurements. Results are intended only to demonstrate the research workflow and should not be interpreted as clinical or real-world fall detection performance.\n\n**Important:** This is only a workflow demonstration. It is not clinical validation, real-world fall detection, or a medical decision system.\n"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
      "source": "# 2. Import Libraries\n\nimport numpy as np\nimport pandas as pd\nimport matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n\nfrom scipy.ndimage import uniform_filter1d\n\nfrom sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split\nfrom sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier\nfrom sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, confusion_matrix, ConfusionMatrixDisplay, classification_report\n\nRANDOM_STATE = 42\nrng = np.random.default_rng(RANDOM_STATE)\n\nprint(\"Libraries imported successfully.\")\n"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": "## 3. Generate Synthetic CSI-Like Signals\n\nIn this notebook:\n\n- **Class 0 = normal activity**\n- **Class 1 = fall-like event**\n\nA normal activity signal is modeled as smooth low-amplitude fluctuations. A fall-like event is modeled as a sudden transient spike followed by recovery.\n\nThis is only a conceptual demonstration. Real WiFi CSI data can be much more complex and may include multiple antennas, subcarriers, amplitude/phase values, hardware artifacts, environmental noise, and human/environmental variability.\n"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
      "source": "def generate_normal_signal(length=200, noise_level=0.05, random_state=None):\n    \"\"\"Generate a synthetic CSI-like signal for normal activity.\n\n    Parameters\n    ----------\n    length : int\n        Number of time samples.\n    noise_level : float\n        Standard deviation of additive noise.\n    random_state : int or None\n        Seed for reproducibility.\n\n    Returns\n    -------\n    np.ndarray\n        Synthetic one-dimensional CSI-like amplitude signal.\n    \"\"\"\n    local_rng = np.random.default_rng(random_state)\n    t = np.linspace(0, 1, length)\n\n    slow_variation = 0.15 * np.sin(2 * np.pi * 3 * t)\n    small_motion = 0.05 * np.sin(2 * np.pi * 12 * t)\n    noise = noise_level * local_rng.normal(size=length)\n\n    return 1.0 + slow_variation + small_motion + noise\n\n\ndef generate_fall_like_signal(length=200, noise_level=0.05, random_state=None):\n    \"\"\"Generate a synthetic CSI-like signal for a fall-like event.\n\n    The event is represented by a transient spike and a short recovery dip.\n    This is a simplified synthetic model, not a real CSI measurement.\n    \"\"\"\n    local_rng = np.random.default_rng(random_state)\n    signal = generate_normal_signal(length=length, noise_level=noise_level, random_state=random_state)\n\n    center = local_rng.integers(low=int(length * 0.35), high=int(length * 0.70))\n    width = local_rng.integers(low=5, high=14)\n    amplitude = local_rng.uniform(0.8, 1.3)\n\n    x = np.arange(length)\n    transient = amplitude * np.exp(-0.5 * ((x - center) / width) ** 2)\n\n    signal = signal + transient\n\n    recovery_start = min(center + width, length - 1)\n    recovery_end = min(center + 3 * width, length)\n    signal[recovery_start:recovery_end] -= 0.15\n\n    return signal\n\n\ndef generate_dataset(n_samples_per_class=100, length=200, random_state=42):\n    \"\"\"Generate a synthetic dataset with normal and fall-like signals.\"\"\"\n    local_rng = np.random.default_rng(random_state)\n    signals = []\n    labels = []\n\n    for _ in range(n_samples_per_class):\n        seed = local_rng.integers(0, 1_000_000)\n        signals.append(generate_normal_signal(length=length, random_state=seed))\n        labels.append(0)\n\n    for _ in range(n_samples_per_class):\n        seed = local_rng.integers(0, 1_000_000)\n        signals.append(generate_fall_like_signal(length=length, random_state=seed))\n        labels.append(1)\n\n    return np.array(signals), np.array(labels)\n\n\nsignals, labels = generate_dataset(n_samples_per_class=150, length=200, random_state=RANDOM_STATE)\n\nprint(\"Signals shape:\", signals.shape)\nprint(\"Labels shape:\", labels.shape)\nprint(\"Class counts:\")\nprint(pd.Series(labels).map({0: \"normal activity\", 1: \"fall-like event\"}).value_counts())\n"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": "## 4. Visualize Normal vs. Fall-Like Signals\n\nThe plots below show examples of synthetic CSI-like amplitude traces. These are not real CSI measurements. They are simple simulated signals designed to make the workflow understandable.\n"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
      "source": "time_index = np.arange(signals.shape[1])\n\nnormal_example = signals[labels == 0][0]\nfall_example = signals[labels == 1][0]\n\nplt.figure(figsize=(10, 4))\nplt.plot(time_index, normal_example, label=\"Normal activity\")\nplt.plot(time_index, fall_example, label=\"Fall-like event\")\nplt.xlabel(\"Time sample\")\nplt.ylabel(\"Synthetic CSI-like amplitude\")\nplt.title(\"Example Synthetic CSI-Like Signals\")\nplt.legend()\nplt.grid(True)\nplt.show()\n"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": "## 5. Preprocess Signals\n\nA simple smoothing filter is applied to reduce high-frequency noise. In real WiFi CSI work, preprocessing may include denoising, phase correction, subcarrier selection, outlier removal, filtering, and normalization.\n"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
      "source": "def smooth_signal(signal, window_size=5):\n    \"\"\"Apply simple moving-average smoothing.\"\"\"\n    return uniform_filter1d(signal, size=window_size)\n\n\ndef normalize_signal(signal):\n    \"\"\"Normalize a signal to zero mean and unit standard deviation.\"\"\"\n    std = np.std(signal)\n    if std == 0:\n        return signal - np.mean(signal)\n    return (signal - np.mean(signal)) / std\n\n\nsmoothed_normal = smooth_signal(normal_example, window_size=7)\nsmoothed_fall = smooth_signal(fall_example, window_size=7)\n\nplt.figure(figsize=(10, 4))\nplt.plot(time_index, normal_example, alpha=0.45, label=\"Original normal\")\nplt.plot(time_index, smoothed_normal, label=\"Smoothed normal\")\nplt.xlabel(\"Time sample\")\nplt.ylabel(\"Synthetic CSI-like amplitude\")\nplt.title(\"Simple Smoothing Example: Normal Activity\")\nplt.legend()\nplt.grid(True)\nplt.show()\n\nplt.figure(figsize=(10, 4))\nplt.plot(time_index, fall_example, alpha=0.45, label=\"Original fall-like\")\nplt.plot(time_index, smoothed_fall, label=\"Smoothed fall-like\")\nplt.xlabel(\"Time sample\")\nplt.ylabel(\"Synthetic CSI-like amplitude\")\nplt.title(\"Simple Smoothing Example: Fall-Like Event\")\nplt.legend()\nplt.grid(True)\nplt.show()\n"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": "## 6. Extract Features\n\nFor this first baseline, we extract simple time-series features:\n\n- mean\n- standard deviation\n- energy\n- peak-to-peak range\n- maximum amplitude\n- minimum amplitude\n- variance\n\nThese features are intentionally simple so the workflow is easy to understand. Future versions can add richer signal-processing features.\n"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
      "source": "def extract_basic_features(signal):\n    \"\"\"Extract simple statistical features from a one-dimensional time-series signal.\"\"\"\n    signal = np.asarray(signal)\n\n    return {\n        \"mean\": np.mean(signal),\n        \"std\": np.std(signal),\n        \"energy\": np.sum(signal ** 2),\n        \"ptp_range\": np.ptp(signal),\n        \"max_value\": np.max(signal),\n        \"min_value\": np.min(signal),\n        \"variance\": np.var(signal),\n    }\n\n\nexample_features = extract_basic_features(smoothed_fall)\nexample_features\n"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": "## 7. Build a Simple Dataset\n\nNow we apply preprocessing and feature extraction to every synthetic signal. The result is a tabular feature matrix that can be used with a basic scikit-learn classifier.\n"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
      "source": "feature_rows = []\n\nfor signal in signals:\n    smoothed = smooth_signal(signal, window_size=7)\n    normalized = normalize_signal(smoothed)\n    feature_rows.append(extract_basic_features(normalized))\n\nX = pd.DataFrame(feature_rows)\ny = labels\n\nprint(\"Feature table shape:\", X.shape)\nX.head()\n"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
      "source": "feature_table = X.copy()\nfeature_table[\"label\"] = y\nfeature_table[\"class_name\"] = feature_table[\"label\"].map({0: \"normal activity\", 1: \"fall-like event\"})\n\nfeature_table.groupby(\"class_name\")[[\"mean\", \"std\", \"energy\", \"ptp_range\", \"max_value\", \"min_value\", \"variance\"]].mean()\n"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": "## 8. Train Baseline Classifier\n\nWe train a simple Random Forest classifier as a baseline. This is not intended to represent an optimized fall detection model. It is only a first demonstration of the ML workflow.\n"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
      "source": "X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(\n    X,\n    y,\n    test_size=0.25,\n    random_state=RANDOM_STATE,\n    stratify=y\n)\n\nmodel = RandomForestClassifier(\n    n_estimators=100,\n    random_state=RANDOM_STATE\n)\n\nmodel.fit(X_train, y_train)\n\nprint(\"Training samples:\", X_train.shape[0])\nprint(\"Testing samples:\", X_test.shape[0])\n"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": "## 9. Evaluate Accuracy and Confusion Matrix\n\nThe metrics below are computed on synthetic data. They should **not** be interpreted as real-world fall detection accuracy.\n"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
      "source": "y_pred = model.predict(X_test)\n\naccuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)\ncm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)\n\nprint(f\"Accuracy on synthetic test data: {accuracy:.3f}\")\nprint()\nprint(\"Classification report:\")\nprint(classification_report(y_test, y_pred, target_names=[\"normal activity\", \"fall-like event\"]))\n\ndisp = ConfusionMatrixDisplay(\n    confusion_matrix=cm,\n    display_labels=[\"normal activity\", \"fall-like event\"]\n)\n\ndisp.plot()\nplt.title(\"Confusion Matrix on Synthetic CSI-Like Data\")\nplt.grid(False)\nplt.show()\n"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": "## 10. Discussion and Limitations\n\nThis notebook demonstrates a simple workflow, not a validated sensing system.\n\nKey limitations:\n\n- The dataset is synthetic and simplified.\n- The signal model does not represent full real-world WiFi CSI behavior.\n- No real subjects, environments, antennas, subcarriers, or devices are included.\n- The classifier performance is not meaningful as clinical or real-world performance.\n- The current workflow does not evaluate adversarial robustness yet.\n- No physical-layer attack is validated in this notebook.\n\nThe purpose is to create a transparent starting point for organizing a WiFi CSI-inspired ML research workflow.\n"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": "## 11. Next Steps\n\nPlanned improvements:\n\n1. Add clearer synthetic perturbation experiments.\n2. Add more preprocessing methods.\n3. Add additional baseline classifiers.\n4. Add feature importance analysis.\n5. Add real public WiFi CSI datasets if they are publicly available, properly licensed, and ethically appropriate.\n6. Extend the threat-model documentation.\n7. Explore adversarial perturbation analysis in a future notebook.\n\nPyTorch may be added later for deep learning-based time-series models after the baseline workflow is complete.\n"
    }
